# 🌌 Spatial Audio — Revised Implementation Plan
### Grounded in Psychoacoustic Science

> **Reference papers:**
> - *Principles of 3D Sound* — covers ITD, ILD, HRTF, pinna notch cues
> - *Spatial Audio Software Replication Research* — covers binaural DSP pipeline, FDN reverb, Dolby/Sony/Apple architecture analysis

---

## ⚠️ Critical Finding: Why the Previous Plan Was Wrong

The prior plan applied generic **EQ dB deltas** (bass cut, treble boost) as the spatial engine. **Both research papers explicitly disprove this approach:**

> *"EQ-Based Distance Illusion... does NOT give any directional information. Such EQ effects are purely timbral changes (no ITD/ILD manipulation), so they can simulate muffling by distance but not spatial placement around the listener."*
> — Principles of 3D Sound, §9

> *"EQ-Based Surround: Uses static low-pass or high-pass filters to simulate a 'rear' channel. This is a crude approximation that lacks the specific timing (ITD) and individualized spectral cues (HRTF) of true spatial audio."*
> — Spatial Audio Software Replication Research, §Comparison

**What actually creates the perception of space in headphones:**

| Cue | Frequency Range | Perceptual Function |
|-----|----------------|---------------------|
| ITD (timing delay) | <1.5 kHz | Left-right horizontal localization |
| ILD (level difference) | >1.5 kHz | Head-shadow left-right cue |
| **Primary pinna notch** | **6–8 kHz** | **Core elevation cue; distinguishes height** |
| **Secondary pinna notch** | **9–12 kHz** | **Resolves front-back ambiguity** |
| Torso/shoulder reflection | 200 Hz–1.5 kHz | Scale / grounding for external sources |
| D/R ratio (reverb) | Broadband | Distance perception |

